The custom of the ancients in depositing treasures or things of great value in their temples, believing that the sanctity of the place would insure their safety, is well known; they themselves even in times of danger often betook themselves thither to escape the vengeance of their enemies3 cp. Caes„ Bell. Civ. iii. 33, 105; Nepos, Hann. ix. 3. When the Gauls took Rome, we read that the senators withdrew to the Capitol, the sacred habitation of the Roman divinities. The modern custom of depositing the dead in and around Christian temples seems to have had a similar origin. The slave says they deposited the gold with Theotimus, who was the priest of the temple of Diana at Ephesus.
